depending on loss activity in any particular period the combined ratio is the sum of the composite ratio and the underwriting expense ratio the combined ratio measures the total profitability of our underwriting operations and does not take into account corporate expenses net investment income or any foreign exchange gain or loss given the nature of our unique underwriting strategy we expect that our combined ratio may also be volatile from period to period financial condition   investments financial contracts receivable financial contracts payable due to prime brokers   our long investments and financial contracts receivable reported in the condensed consolidated balance sheets as of march    were  million  compared to  million as of december    an increase of  million  or    return to table of contents the significant changes in our long investments and financial contracts receivable for the three months ended march   were as follows increase decrease  in millions   explanation    commodities  gold   decrease primarily due to the reduction of physical gold holdings    financial contracts receivable   decrease in derivative assets partially due to the decrease in unrealized gains relating to derivatives held as of march      equities  listed   increase primarily due to acquisition of equity securities    corporate debt   decrease due to disposal of certain corporate debt instruments as of march    our exposure to long investments decreased to   compared to  as of december    this exposure analysis is conducted on a deltaadjusted basis and excludes macro positions which consist of cds interest rate swaps sovereign debt currencies commodities volatility indexes and derivatives on any of these instruments therefore a change in the exposure may not directly translate into a corresponding change in the long investments   financial contracts payable as of march   increased by  million  or   compared to december    primarily due to a total return equity swaps that depreci